<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
	Guided Lecture Notes worksheet: "Undetermined Coefficients"
	Book sections (Exploring Differential Equations, geoff-cox/debookrs):
		c9-uc/sec-lncc-eqns.ptx
		c9-uc/sec-selecting-the-particular-soln.ptx
		c9-uc/sec-uc-method.ptx
	Old deck: source/notes/latex/ folder "05 lncc".
	Previous worksheet: ws-homogeneous-linear.ptx; next: ws-laplace-transforms.

	Per the sourcing rules, every equation here is fresh: concepts mirror
	the book, but none of the example equations appear in it (nor in the
	old deck or the earlier worksheets). Per the instructor overrides in
	CLAUDE.md section 4: no interactive content, and the whole topic stays
	on this one worksheet.

	Worksheet conventions: checklists/worksheet-conventions.md (see
	CLAUDE.md section 4 for this repo's parameters). In brief:
	  * Student/instructor split via component="stu" / component="key",
	    mirrored in structure; answers never live inside <fillin>.
	  * Worked problems: paired <exercise component="stu" workspace="Xin">
	    and <exercise component="key"> (statement + solution).
	  * True/False checks: one <exercise> + <solution component="key">.
	  * <page> = vertical print space, not topics; headings are
	    <p><term>...</term></p>; display math uses <md> (<me>/<men> are
	    prohibited here).
-->
<worksheet xml:id="ws-undetermined-coefficients" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
	<title>Undetermined Coefficients</title>

	<objectives>
		<ul>
			<li><p><term>Recognize</term> LNCC equations and the two-part structure of their general solutions, <m>y = y_h + y_p</m>.</p></li>
			<li><p><term>Select</term> the form of a particular solution <m>y_p</m> to mirror the forcing function <m>f(x)</m>.</p></li>
			<li><p><term>Modify</term> <m>y_p</m> by factors of <m>x</m> when it conflicts with the homogeneous solution.</p></li>
			<li><p><term>Determine</term> the unknown coefficients by substituting and matching like-terms.</p></li>
			<li><p><term>Assemble</term> and report the full general solution.</p></li>
		</ul>
	</objectives>

	<!-- ==================================================================== -->
	<!-- PAGE 1 : LNCC equations; y = y_h + y_p                               -->
	<!-- ==================================================================== -->

	<page>
		<p><term>Turning the forcing on.</term></p>

		<p>
			Last worksheet the right-hand side was zero&#8212;nothing pushed on
			the system. A <term>linear nonhomogeneous constant coefficient</term>
			(LNCC) equation restores the push: <m>a\,y'' + b\,y' + c\,y = f(x)</m>
			with a nonzero forcing function <m>f(x)</m>. Its general solution has
			two parts: the <em>homogeneous solution</em> <m>y_h</m> (last
			worksheet's machinery, carrying the arbitrary constants) plus any one
			<em>particular solution</em> <m>y_p</m> that produces the forcing.
		</p>

		<!-- Reading check -->
		<p>
			<term>Reading check.</term> Fill in each blank from your reading.
			<ol>
				<li>
					<p component="stu">
						An LNCC equation differs from an LHCC equation only in having a
						nonzero <fillin characters="16"/>. Its general solution is the
						sum <m>y = y_h + y_p</m>, where <m>y_h</m> carries the arbitrary
						<fillin characters="9"/> and <m>y_p</m> is any one solution of
						the full equation.
					</p>
					<p component="key">
						An LNCC equation differs from an LHCC equation only in having a
						nonzero <m>\underline{\textbf{forcing function}}</m>. Its general
						solution is the sum <m>y = y_h + y_p</m>, where <m>y_h</m>
						carries the arbitrary <m>\underline{\textbf{constants}}</m> and
						<m>y_p</m> is any one solution of the full equation.
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</p>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-uc-tf-sum">
			<title>True or False</title>
			<statement>
				<p>If <m>y_p</m> solves <m>a\,y'' + b\,y' + c\,y = f(x)</m> and <m>y_h</m> solves the matching homogeneous equation, then <m>y_p + y_h</m> also solves the full equation.</p>
			</statement>
			<solution component="key">
				<p>
					True. Substituting the sum, the <m>y_h</m> part contributes
					<m>0</m> and the <m>y_p</m> part contributes <m>f(x)</m>&#8212;linearity
					lets the two ride along without disturbing each other. That is
					exactly why the general solution is <m>y_h + y_p</m>: the
					homogeneous family supplies the flexibility, the particular
					solution supplies the forcing.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-uc-ex-structure" component="stu" workspace="2.6in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Consider
					<md>
						<mrow> y'' - y' - 2y = -4x. </mrow>
					</md>
					(a) Solve the matching homogeneous equation to find <m>y_h</m>.
					(b) Verify that <m>y_p = 2x - 1</m> solves the full equation.
					(c) Write the general solution.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-uc-ex-structure" component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Consider
					<md>
						<mrow> y'' - y' - 2y = -4x. </mrow>
					</md>
					(a) Solve the matching homogeneous equation to find <m>y_h</m>.
					(b) Verify that <m>y_p = 2x - 1</m> solves the full equation.
					(c) Write the general solution.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					(a) The characteristic equation of <m>y'' - y' - 2y = 0</m> is
					<m>r^2 - r - 2 = (r-2)(r+1) = 0</m>, so
					<m>y_h = c_1 e^{2x} + c_2 e^{-x}</m>.
				</p>
				<p>
					(b) With <m>y_p = 2x - 1</m>: <m>y_p' = 2</m>, <m>y_p'' = 0</m>, so
					<md>
						<mrow> 0 - 2 - 2(2x - 1) = -2 - 4x + 2 = -4x. \checkmark </mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
				<p>
					(c) <m>y = c_1 e^{2x} + c_2 e^{-x} + 2x - 1</m>. Notice the roles:
					the two constants live entirely in <m>y_h</m>; <m>y_p</m> is a
					single fixed function whose only job is to manufacture the
					forcing.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ==================================================================== -->
	<!-- PAGE 2 : Selecting the form of y_p                                    -->
	<!-- ==================================================================== -->

	<page>
		<p><term>Guessing with structure: selecting <m>y_p</m>.</term></p>

		<p>
			Where does <m>y_p</m> come from? Derivatives of polynomials are
			polynomials, of exponentials are exponentials, of sines and cosines
			are sines and cosines&#8212;so <m>y_p</m> should <em>mirror the
			structural form</em> of <m>f(x)</m>, with unknown letters
			<m>A, B, C, \ldots</m> (the <term>undetermined coefficients</term>)
			standing in for the numbers we will solve for later.
		</p>

		<!-- Reading check -->
		<p>
			<term>Reading check.</term> Fill in each blank from your reading.
			<ol>
				<li>
					<p component="stu">
						Even if a lower-order term is missing from a polynomial
						<m>f(x)</m>, the form of <m>y_p</m> must still
						<fillin characters="7"/> it: for <m>f(x) = 5x^2</m> the correct
						starting form is <m>y_p = Ax^2 + Bx + </m><fillin characters="2"/>.
					</p>
					<p component="key">
						Even if a lower-order term is missing from a polynomial
						<m>f(x)</m>, the form of <m>y_p</m> must still
						<m>\underline{\textbf{include}}</m> it: for <m>f(x) = 5x^2</m>
						the correct starting form is
						<m>y_p = Ax^2 + Bx + \underline{\textbf{C}}</m>.
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</p>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-uc-ex-forms" component="stu" workspace="2.2in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					For each forcing function, write the starting form of <m>y_p</m>
					(do not solve for the coefficients):
					<md>
						<mrow> \text{(a)}\ f(x) = 6x - 2 \qquad
						       \text{(b)}\ f(x) = 4e^{7x} </mrow>
						<mrow> \text{(c)}\ f(x) = 2\sin(5x) \qquad
						       \text{(d)}\ f(x) = 8x^2 </mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-uc-ex-forms" component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					For each forcing function, write the starting form of <m>y_p</m>
					(do not solve for the coefficients):
					<md>
						<mrow> \text{(a)}\ f(x) = 6x - 2 \qquad
						       \text{(b)}\ f(x) = 4e^{7x} </mrow>
						<mrow> \text{(c)}\ f(x) = 2\sin(5x) \qquad
						       \text{(d)}\ f(x) = 8x^2 </mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					(a) <m>y_p = Ax + B</m> (a full degree-one polynomial).
				</p>
				<p>
					(b) <m>y_p = Ae^{7x}</m>&#8212;the exponent is <em>known</em>; only
					the multiplier is undetermined.
				</p>
				<p>
					(c) <m>y_p = A\sin(5x) + B\cos(5x)</m>. Both siblings are required
					even though <m>f</m> shows only sine&#8212;differentiation swaps
					sines and cosines, so <m>y_p</m> needs both to have any hope of
					matching.
				</p>
				<p>
					(d) <m>y_p = Ax^2 + Bx + C</m>: the missing <m>x</m> and constant
					terms must still be included, since derivatives of <m>x^2</m>
					produce them.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-uc-tf-sine">
			<title>True or False</title>
			<statement>
				<p>For <m>f(x) = 3\sin(2x)</m>, the guess <m>y_p = A\sin(2x)</m> (no cosine term) is sufficient.</p>
			</statement>
			<solution component="key">
				<p>
					False in general. Substituting <m>A\sin(2x)</m> into an equation
					with a <m>y'</m> term produces cosine terms on the left that have
					no partner on the right, forcing <m>A</m> into contradictory
					duties. The sine-cosine pair
					<m>A\sin(2x) + B\cos(2x)</m> gives the algebra enough freedom.
					(Only when the equation has no odd-order derivatives can the lone
					sine survive.)
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ==================================================================== -->
	<!-- PAGE 3 : The conflict rule; a full solve with modification           -->
	<!-- ==================================================================== -->

	<page>
		<p><term>The conflict rule: when the guess is already taken.</term></p>

		<p>
			One wrinkle: if the selected <m>y_p</m> shares a term with
			<m>y_h</m>, substituting it produces <m>0</m>, not <m>f(x)</m>&#8212;the
			homogeneous solution swallows the guess. The repair: multiply the
			conflicting terms by <m>x</m>, and repeat until nothing is shared.
		</p>

		<!-- Reading check -->
		<p>
			<term>Reading check.</term> Fill in each blank from your reading.
			<ol>
				<li>
					<p component="stu">
						<term>Step 1.</term> Solve the homogeneous equation for
						<m>y_h</m>. <term>Step 2.</term> Select the form of <m>y_p</m>
						from <m>f(x)</m>. <term>Step 3.</term> If <m>y_p</m> shares a
						term with <m>y_h</m>, multiply the conflicting terms by
						<fillin characters="3"/>. <term>Step 4.</term> Substitute and
						match <fillin characters="12"/> to find the coefficients.
						<term>Step 5.</term> Report <m>y = y_h + y_p</m>.
					</p>
					<p component="key">
						<term>Step 1.</term> Solve the homogeneous equation for
						<m>y_h</m>. <term>Step 2.</term> Select the form of <m>y_p</m>
						from <m>f(x)</m>. <term>Step 3.</term> If <m>y_p</m> shares a
						term with <m>y_h</m>, multiply the conflicting terms by
						<m>\underline{\textbf{x}}</m>. <term>Step 4.</term> Substitute
						and match <m>\underline{\textbf{like-terms}}</m> to find the
						coefficients. <term>Step 5.</term> Report <m>y = y_h + y_p</m>.
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</p>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-uc-ex-conflict" component="stu" workspace="3.4in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Solve
					<md>
						<mrow> y'' - 9y = 4e^{3x}. </mrow>
					</md>
					(a) Find <m>y_h</m> and explain why the natural guess
					<m>y_p = Ae^{3x}</m> fails.
					(b) Repair the guess and find the coefficient.
					(c) Write the general solution.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-uc-ex-conflict" component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Solve
					<md>
						<mrow> y'' - 9y = 4e^{3x}. </mrow>
					</md>
					(a) Find <m>y_h</m> and explain why the natural guess
					<m>y_p = Ae^{3x}</m> fails.
					(b) Repair the guess and find the coefficient.
					(c) Write the general solution.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					(a) From <m>r^2 - 9 = 0</m>, <m>y_h = c_1 e^{3x} + c_2 e^{-3x}</m>.
					The guess <m>Ae^{3x}</m> is already a homogeneous solution, so
					substituting it yields <m>0 = 4e^{3x}</m>&#8212;impossible. The
					forcing resonates with the system's own response.
				</p>
				<p>
					(b) Multiply by <m>x</m>: try <m>y_p = A\,x\,e^{3x}</m>. Then
					<md>
						<mrow> y_p' \amp = A e^{3x}(1 + 3x), \qquad y_p'' = A e^{3x}(6 + 9x), </mrow>
						<mrow> y_p'' - 9y_p \amp = A e^{3x}(6 + 9x) - 9A\,x\,e^{3x} = 6A e^{3x}. </mrow>
					</md>
					Matching <m>6A e^{3x} = 4e^{3x}</m> gives <m>A = \tfrac{2}{3}</m>.
				</p>
				<p>
					(c)
					<md>
						<mrow> y = c_1 e^{3x} + c_2 e^{-3x} + \tfrac{2}{3}\,x\,e^{3x}. </mrow>
					</md>
					The <m>x</m>-factor is the same medicine that cured the
					repeated-root case last worksheet&#8212;and for the same reason:
					the plain exponential was already spoken for.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-uc-tf-alwaysx">
			<title>True or False</title>
			<statement>
				<p>To be safe, you should always multiply <m>y_p</m> by <m>x</m>, whether or not it conflicts with <m>y_h</m>.</p>
			</statement>
			<solution component="key">
				<p>
					False. An unnecessary factor of <m>x</m> wrecks the match: the
					substituted guess produces terms (like <m>x e^{kx}</m>) that
					<m>f(x)</m> does not contain, and the coefficient system becomes
					inconsistent. Multiply by <m>x</m> exactly when a conflict with
					<m>y_h</m> demands it&#8212;no more, no less.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ==================================================================== -->
	<!-- PAGE 4 : The full method start to finish                              -->
	<!-- ==================================================================== -->

	<page>
		<p><term>The whole method, start to finish.</term></p>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-uc-ex-full" component="stu" workspace="3.6in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the general solution of
					<md>
						<mrow> y'' + 2y' - 3y = 6x + 1 </mrow>
					</md>
					by running all five steps: <m>y_h</m>, select <m>y_p</m>, check
					for conflicts, match coefficients, and assemble
					<m>y = y_h + y_p</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-uc-ex-full" component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the general solution of
					<md>
						<mrow> y'' + 2y' - 3y = 6x + 1 </mrow>
					</md>
					by running all five steps: <m>y_h</m>, select <m>y_p</m>, check
					for conflicts, match coefficients, and assemble
					<m>y = y_h + y_p</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					<term>Step 1.</term> <m>r^2 + 2r - 3 = (r+3)(r-1) = 0</m>, so
					<m>y_h = c_1 e^{-3x} + c_2 e^{x}</m>.
				</p>
				<p>
					<term>Step 2.</term> <m>f(x) = 6x + 1</m> is a degree-one
					polynomial: guess <m>y_p = Ax + B</m>.
				</p>
				<p>
					<term>Step 3.</term> No conflict&#8212;<m>y_h</m> contains only
					exponentials.
				</p>
				<p>
					<term>Step 4.</term> With <m>y_p' = A</m> and <m>y_p'' = 0</m>:
					<md>
						<mrow> 0 + 2A - 3(Ax + B) \amp = -3A\,x + (2A - 3B) = 6x + 1. </mrow>
					</md>
					Matching <m>x</m>-terms: <m>-3A = 6</m>, so <m>A = -2</m>. Matching
					free terms: <m>2(-2) - 3B = 1</m>, so <m>B = -\tfrac{5}{3}</m>.
				</p>
				<p>
					<term>Step 5.</term>
					<md>
						<mrow> y = c_1 e^{-3x} + c_2 e^{x} - 2x - \tfrac{5}{3}. </mrow>
					</md>
					A quick sanity check on the free term: at any <m>x</m>, the
					<m>y_p</m> pieces alone must reproduce <m>6x + 1</m>&#8212;and they
					do.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<conclusion>
			<title>Looking ahead</title>
			<p>
				Undetermined coefficients works beautifully when the forcing is
				polite&#8212;polynomials, exponentials, sines and cosines. But real
				systems get switched on and off, struck, and jolted by forcing
				functions with corners and jumps. The next worksheets build the
				<em>Laplace transform</em>, a machine designed to handle exactly
				that kind of forcing.
			</p>
		</conclusion>
	</page>
</worksheet>
